By: Kim Huston ‚Ä¢ Posted: May 13, 2020

So far in the COVID-19 pandemic, data from China, Italy and other European countries showed that coronavirus infections were much less common in (1/*)

‚Äî called pediatric multisystem inflammatory syndrome potentially associated with COVID-19 ‚Äî that look a lot like a disease known as Kawasaki disease.

What is Kawasaki disease?
The disease was named for pediatrician Tomisaku Kawasaki, M.D., the first physician to document (3/*)

functioning of some heart valves. Children who experience heart complications from Kawasaki disease may need surgery and/or lifelong heart care.

COVID-19 and Kawasaki disease connection?
Some interesting reports began to emerge from England in late April: In one week, (10/*)

eight children were admitted to a hospital in London with a hyperinflammatory state.

‚ÄúOf course, it was happening at a time when there were lots of COVID-19 cases,‚Äù said Kristina A. Bryant, M.D., pediatric infectious disease specialist with Norton Children‚Äôs Infectious (11/*)

infection.

‚ÄúTurns out they actually did have COVID-19 infections,‚Äù Dr. Bryant said.

Since the initial report from London, multiple children‚Äôs hospitals in the U.S., primarily on the East Coast, have reported treating children who have been admitted with this multisystem (13/*)

bacterial infection called toxic shock. Most of the time toxic shock is caused by staph or strep germs, but in fact some of these children have been infected with COVID-19.‚Äù

‚ÄúThe patients that they‚Äôre seeing in New York City now who have this Kawasaki disease-like illness (15/*)
